      "id": "pt_ush_p1_u7_044",
      "unit": 7,
      "question": "A historian argues that the federal judiciary posed a significant obstacle to Progressive Era reform efforts in the early twentieth century. Which of the following pieces of evidence would best support this interpretation?\n\nA) The Clayton Antitrust Act of 1914 strengthened federal authority to regulate monopolistic business practices.\nB) The Supreme Court's ruling in Lochner v. New York (1905) struck down a state law limiting bakers' working hours by invoking the liberty of contract doctrine.\nC) Progressive reformers successfully lobbied Congress to establish the Federal Trade Commission to oversee business conduct.\nD) The Sixteenth Amendment granted Congress the power to levy a federal income tax, redistributing the tax burden onto wealthier Americans.",
