      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Supply-side economics, often called 'Reaganomics' or 'trickle-down economics,' was premised on the idea that cutting taxes on higher earners and businesses would incentivize investment, capital formation, and entrepreneurship, generating economic growth that would eventually benefit all Americans. Option A describes a demand-side logic - focused on boosting consumer spending and aggregate demand - that stands in direct contrast to supply-side theory. While this kind of reasoning shares some overlap with Keynesian-adjacent thinking, it is worth noting that Keynesian economics more precisely emphasizes government expenditure rather than tax cuts to lower-income households as the primary driver of demand. Option C is incorrect because Reagan's tax cuts maintained a progressive structure - they reduced rates but did not eliminate progressivity. Option D misrepresents the policy's intent; Reagan actually sought to increase military spending alongside tax cuts, a combination that contributed to significant deficit growth.",
